{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477736","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477736"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:04:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14710"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14710","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14710"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.12,0.02,0.17,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7403"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115851"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7403","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7403"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14710"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97851"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1607"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18076"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48006"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49128"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49129"},{"type":"contributions","id":"49131"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115851"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn eight-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a two-week history of severe constipation that has progressed to no passage of stool or wind for four days, with abdominal distension and reduced appetite. He reports crampy lower abdominal discomfort and has been avoiding the toilet at school. Before this episode, he had a six-month pattern of infrequent, painful bowel motions and intermittent soiling of underwear, passing a stool every five to seven days that was large and hard, sometimes with streaks of bright red blood on the paper after straining.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has no significant medical history. He does not take any regular medications. There has been no vomiting, bilious emesis, fever, weight loss, or night sweats. He was toilet trained at four years and, according to his parent, passed meconium on day one of life. He eats a varied diet but prefers low-fibre snacks and drinks one to two cups of water during school hours. There is no recent travel and no family history of coeliac disease, thyroid disease, or inflammatory bowel disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable but not toxic. His pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 100/62 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His weight is 28 kg and height is 132 cm, tracking on his usual centiles with BMI 16.1 kg/m2. The abdomen is distended but soft with a palpable firm mass in the left lower quadrant and generalised tympany without peritonism. Bowel sounds are present. Perianal inspection shows mild fissuring without tags or fistulae. Lower limb power, tone, reflexes, and gait are normal; the lumbosacral skin is intact without dimples or hair tufts. No laboratory tests have been performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence stimulant laxatives","Refer to surgery for manual disimpaction","Refer for colonoscopy","Order abdominal X-ray","Commence oral polyethylene glycol"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EObstipation is a severe form of constipation with failure to pass stool or wind, reflecting substantial faecal loading and withholding. In a well child with normal growth and no red flags for obstruction or systemic disease, the priority is complete disimpaction followed by maintenance and behavioural strategies. Clinical findings of a palpable stool mass, abdominal distension, fissure-related bleeding, and a history of painful, infrequent stools support functional faecal retention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence oral polyethylene glycol\u003C/strong\u003E is appropriate because it provides prompt distal clearance to reduce pain and withholding, then transitions to high-dose oral polyethylene glycol to complete disimpaction and maintain soft, regular stools. Scheduled toilet sits, reward systems, education about stool withholding, and sensible dietary fibre and fluids support long-term success.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrder abdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not required when stool loading is evident clinically and there are no red flags such as bilious vomiting, severe pain with peritonism, systemic illness, or growth faltering. Imaging adds radiation and rarely alters initial management in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer for colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is unwarranted because there is normal growth, no chronic diarrhoea, no persistent rectal bleeding beyond fissure-related streaking, and no systemic symptoms such as fever or weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer to surgery for manual disimpaction\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for cases where medical management has failed or there are complications such as bowel perforation. Manual disimpaction under anaesthesia carries risks and is not first-line treatment for functional obstipation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence stimulant laxatives\u003C/strong\u003E alone overlooks the need to clear the retained stool mass. Stimulants may be used as adjuncts, but without an initial oral polyethylene glycol regimen, they may increase cramping and perpetuate withholding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In children with suspected obstipation, confirm faecal loading clinically and screen for red flags before investigations.","Effective faecal disimpaction is the priority; high-dose oral polyethylene glycol is first-line treatment.","Imaging and endoscopy are reserved for alarm features or diagnostic uncertainty and are not required when functional faecal loading is clear."],"references":["Jani B, Marsicano E. Constipation: Evaluation and Management. Mo Med. 2018 May-Jun;115(3):236-240. PMID: 30228729; PMCID: PMC6140151.","Pelletier JF, Higgins GL 3rd, Haydar SA. Obstipation unresponsive to usual therapeutic maneuvers. J Fam Pract. 2012 Jun;61(6):353-5. PMID: 22670240.","The Royal Children\u0027s Hospital, Melbourne, Australia, Clinical Practice Guideline on constipation, [Internet, last updated  March 2020; cited 25 September 2025], Available from: https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/constipation/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97851"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14710"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97851","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97851"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-25T18:55:32+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-25T18:56:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7403"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115851"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",